The most common form of conditional block is using the multiline template tag syntax. Let's type out a simple example: # {% if system.hostname == "epic-desktop" %}
displays = ["DP-1", "DP-2"]
# {% if system.hostname == "business-desktop" %}
displays = ["HDMI-1", "HDMI-2"]
# {% else %}
displays = ["eDP-1"]
# {% end %} Now, this is of course not a valid configuration just yet, as we're setting the displays variable thrice. However, once you run yolk sync, yolk will evaluate the condition and comment out the blocks that don't apply. For example, on your laptop, this config might be turned into: # {% if system.hostname == "epic-desktop" %}
#<yolk> displays = ["DP-1", "DP-2"]
# {% if system.hostname == "business-desktop" %}
#<yolk> displays = ["HDMI-1", "HDMI-2"]
# {% else %}
displays = ["eDP-1"]
# {% end %} Note thta yolk added a special <yolk> prefix to the comments. Yolk conditionals will only ever add or remove comments with this prefix, which means that you can still have regular comments in those conditional blocks.

